02:12.999 --> 02:14.299
      Hey, uh, Dr. Crane,       

02:14.334 --> 02:16.335
          after you're done with
      that paper, can I have it?

02:16.369 --> 02:18.070
Well, actually, I planned       
      on saving it, Woody.      

02:18.104 --> 02:19.138
  See, there's an article here  

02:19.172 --> 02:20.739
    on the ins and out          
    of buying diamonds          

02:20.774 --> 02:22.775
    and I was thinking          
of buying Lilith a brooch.      

02:22.809 --> 02:26.078
      Oh, okay, uh... see, I was
     wanting to clip the coupons

02:26.112 --> 02:28.147
    'cause I'm trying to make   
         it to my next paycheck,

02:28.181 --> 02:29.715
        but, uh, I don't want   
          to cut up your article

02:29.749 --> 02:32.885
                    on jewels   
                and diamonds.   

02:32.919 --> 02:35.054
Here's the paper,               
Woody.                          

02:35.088 --> 02:36.822
You know, Lilith and I          
are actually making             

02:36.856 --> 02:38.757
some economic concessions       
as well.                        

02:38.792 --> 02:41.527
 Well, for instance, I decided  
    not to buy that new BMW.    

02:41.561 --> 02:42.561
                        Really? 

02:42.595 --> 02:43.629
That's right.                   

02:43.663 --> 02:45.364
            So, uh,             
what are the coupons for?       

02:45.398 --> 02:48.200
                         Food.  

02:48.234 --> 02:50.069
         You know what?         

02:50.103 --> 02:51.637
 I'm going to stop talking now. 

02:53.306 --> 02:55.674
Top of the morning to you.      

02:57.344 --> 02:59.778
         So, uh, how do you like
          my outfit there, Norm?

02:59.813 --> 03:00.779
                          Cliff,

03:00.814 --> 03:02.314
    you're my friend.           

03:02.349 --> 03:05.651
I haven't judged you in the past
and I'm not going to start now. 

03:05.685 --> 03:07.986
                 Hey, uh, listen
                  up, everybody.

03:08.021 --> 03:09.321
        I've got an announcement
                to make here.   

03:09.356 --> 03:12.925
 Yours truly has been selected  
 by the USPS for a reenactment  

03:12.959 --> 03:16.795
of the first mail delivery down 
the venerable Boston Post Road. 

03:16.830 --> 03:18.931
     Yeah, I'm going to be,     
    uh, riding a horse          

03:18.965 --> 03:21.834
        on the last leg         
from Hingham to the Central P.O.

03:21.868 --> 03:24.069
          (chuckling):          
  Yeah, that's why I'm dressed  
        this way.               

03:24.104 --> 03:25.771
        What way?               

03:25.805 --> 03:30.476
      Oh, you know, this,       
this crazy looking outfit.      

03:30.510 --> 03:33.512
          Boy, are you          
     splitting hairs today.     

03:33.580 --> 03:35.381
             Cliffie, Cliff, you
             can't ride a horse.

03:35.415 --> 03:36.615
                You're afraid   
                      of horses.

03:36.649 --> 03:37.850
        How do you know?        

03:37.917 --> 03:39.284
            I know you're afraid
         of that little carousel

03:39.386 --> 03:42.621
                     in front of
                     the market.

03:42.655 --> 03:44.623
That was                        
a safety concern, Norm.         

03:44.657 --> 03:45.758
                 Is that why you
                 were screaming,

03:45.792 --> 03:48.560
              "Stop, stop, we're
              all going to die"?

03:48.595 --> 03:50.963
I was concerned                 
about the kids, Norm.           

03:50.997 --> 03:52.598
Is that so wrong?               

03:53.700 --> 03:56.135
  Boy, Cliff, I am so jealous.  

03:56.169 --> 03:57.703
     I used to love horses.     

03:57.771 --> 03:59.004
You know,                       
when I was a little girl,       

03:59.039 --> 04:02.041
every weekend                   
I would ride my pony,           

04:02.108 --> 04:04.510
 an-an-and I would feed my pony 
          sugar cubes           

04:04.544 --> 04:07.179
  and little bits of chocolate  
    and, and Snickers.          

04:07.213 --> 04:08.380
     They really like that.     

04:08.448 --> 04:11.350
And sometimes I would give      
my pony some Snickers,          

04:11.384 --> 04:14.019
      and then I would eat      
         some Snickers.         

04:14.054 --> 04:17.022
      And then other times      
I would eat all the sugar cubes 

04:17.057 --> 04:19.458
    and the chocolate           
        and the Snickers        

04:19.492 --> 04:22.394
before I ever got               
to the stable.                  

04:22.429 --> 04:24.530
    And then one time           
  my riding instructor told me  

04:24.564 --> 04:27.032
I couldn't ride my pony anymore.

04:28.535 --> 04:29.935
Why, Miss Howe?                 

04:30.036 --> 04:34.373
            Well, he said that I
             had... outgrown it.

04:36.042 --> 04:38.077
            I don't want to talk
             about this anymore.

04:38.111 --> 04:40.312
                          CLIFF:
        Well, I hope you'll all,
            uh, tune in tonight.

04:40.347 --> 04:42.414
Uh, the, uh, local news         

04:42.449 --> 04:43.949
is going to show                
my triumphant ride              

04:43.983 --> 04:45.150
to the post office.             

04:45.185 --> 04:46.385
                    (chuckling):
         Yeah, it's a big moment

04:46.419 --> 04:48.020
    for me.                     

04:48.054 --> 04:50.456
Yeah, it's, it's a high point   
of my career.                   

04:50.490 --> 04:53.692
No, it's a high point           
of my entire life.              

04:56.429 --> 04:58.397
Hey, why's Cliffie dressed      
like that?                      

04:58.431 --> 05:01.533
                      I forget. 

05:01.568 --> 05:04.470
         (sing-songy):          
             Sa-am.             

05:04.504 --> 05:06.238
              What are you doing
                down here, Hill?

05:06.272 --> 05:09.108
                Hair Club For   
                    Men meeting?

05:09.142 --> 05:12.411
Oh, I didn't see you            
down there, Miss Tortelli.      

05:12.445 --> 05:13.679
Although frankly you do...      

05:13.713 --> 05:14.680
    (sniffs)                    

05:14.714 --> 05:17.216
...announce your presence.      

05:17.250 --> 05:19.551
                    So, have you
              decided what color

05:19.586 --> 05:22.187
             you're going to dye
        your head for Easter?   

05:22.222 --> 05:25.457
Why don't you just scuttle      
under the office door           

05:25.492 --> 05:26.825
and get Sam?                    

05:26.860 --> 05:29.828
            Sam, Hill's here!   

05:29.863 --> 05:31.663
Don't tell me.                  

05:31.698 --> 05:33.232
Pizza for lunch?                

05:34.901 --> 05:36.301
        Hi, John.               

05:36.336 --> 05:37.336
        What's up?              

05:37.370 --> 05:38.737
Sa-am, we have a problem.       

05:38.838 --> 05:39.805
                    You know,   

05:39.839 --> 05:41.106
    I got to be honest          
        with you, John.         

05:41.141 --> 05:43.442
        The way you pronounce   
         my name really bugs me.

05:43.476 --> 05:45.110
How would you like me           
to pronounce it?                

05:45.145 --> 05:47.212
                  Sam, just Sam.

05:47.247 --> 05:48.247
                You try it.     

05:48.281 --> 05:50.582
         Sa-am...               

05:50.617 --> 05:53.652
                      All right,
                     John, uh...

05:53.687 --> 05:56.488
  what would you say if you were
  going to order a ham sandwich?

05:56.556 --> 05:59.124
     I don't eat ha-am.         

05:59.159 --> 06:00.926
                    Never mind. 

06:00.960 --> 06:02.895
                     What, what 
                do you want?    

06:02.929 --> 06:05.964
My busboy informs me            
that the Dumpsters are full.    

06:05.999 --> 06:07.499
                Our Dumpsters   
                    are full.   

06:07.534 --> 06:08.634
                      What's the
                    big problem?

06:08.668 --> 06:09.601
              Aha!              

06:09.669 --> 06:11.136
  They are not <i>our</i> Dumpsters.   

06:11.171 --> 06:13.005
     They are <i>my</i> Dumpsters.     

06:13.039 --> 06:14.740
If that's confusing,            

06:14.774 --> 06:16.542
perhaps I'll have               
a likeness of your face         

06:16.576 --> 06:20.045
painted on the Dumpster with    
a bold line drawn through it.   

06:20.113 --> 06:24.817
In fact, I'll do that anyway... 
    just for a giggle.          

06:24.851 --> 06:27.186
Perhaps                         
I'll have buttons made up.      

06:27.253 --> 06:29.154
I'll make it a whole thing.     

06:29.222 --> 06:32.658
Hey, Hill, you can't order us   
around like that.               

06:32.692 --> 06:34.893
Sammy can do anything he wants  
with his trash.                 

06:34.928 --> 06:37.996
        Yes, I see today he's   
      dressed it up in an apron.

06:40.100 --> 06:42.701
I guess you know all about      
dressing up, huh, Hill?         

06:45.905 --> 06:47.873
                Sam, if any more
                  of your refuse

06:47.907 --> 06:50.175
is deposited in my Dumpsters,   
          I'll have them emptied

06:50.210 --> 06:51.443
in the center                   
of this bar,                    

06:51.478 --> 06:52.878
and if it happens               
again,                          

06:52.912 --> 06:55.647
    I'll do something           
  your customers will notice.   

06:59.452 --> 07:01.420
    Can you believe that guy?   

07:01.454 --> 07:04.323
            Him and his niggling
     little nit-picking details.

07:04.357 --> 07:05.357
    I mean, who cares           

07:05.392 --> 07:06.859
if I stick stuff                
in his Dumpster?                

07:06.893 --> 07:08.027
                    Actually,   
                          Sammy,

07:08.061 --> 07:09.428
             you know, Dumpsters
        are kind of expensive   

07:09.562 --> 07:11.397
          to maintain and empty.

07:11.464 --> 07:14.066
He's been kind of generous to   
let you use them for so long.   

07:14.100 --> 07:16.435
            After all, the guy's
             running a business.

07:16.503 --> 07:18.237
Good point, Norm, good point.   

07:18.338 --> 07:20.973
Speaking of business,           

07:21.007 --> 07:24.243
w-w-what do you think           
we ought to do about, uh,       

07:24.277 --> 07:26.345
    your bar tab here, hmm?     

07:28.014 --> 07:30.482
            We could throw it   
            in <i>our</i> Dumpsters.   

07:38.992 --> 07:41.560
Hey, Miss Howe, Mr. Hill put    
a lock on the Dumpster.         

07:41.594 --> 07:43.228
What should I do with this?     

07:43.263 --> 07:44.630
            Well, just set it   
                 down someplace.

07:44.764 --> 07:46.699
         All right.             

07:49.669 --> 07:52.404
  Cliffie, you want to, uh, pass
     me the sports page, please?

07:52.439 --> 07:54.506
Mr. Peterson,                   
that's just a bag of garbage    

07:54.541 --> 07:55.974
you're talking to.              

07:56.042 --> 07:58.243
          Come here, Woody.     

07:58.278 --> 07:59.645
             Maybe if we all cut
              Cliff a little bit

07:59.713 --> 08:01.914
        of slack, he wouldn't be
        such a "bag of garbage,"

08:01.948 --> 08:03.882
          as you put it, okay?  

08:07.287 --> 08:08.420
                  Do you believe
                    that guy?   

08:08.455 --> 08:11.123
    He stuck a padlock          
    on our Dumpsters.           

08:11.191 --> 08:12.391
 You know, just once, just once 

08:12.425 --> 08:15.494
I would like to do something    
to really stick it to him.      

08:15.562 --> 08:16.862
                Sammy, forget   
                    about it.   

08:16.896 --> 08:18.997
                    You'll never
                  beat that guy.

08:19.032 --> 08:20.766
Hmm, you're right.              

08:20.800 --> 08:22.034
Who am I kidding?               

08:22.068 --> 08:23.268
I'm no match                    
for that guy.                   

08:23.303 --> 08:24.737
He's too evil.                  

08:26.806 --> 08:29.041
What am I thinking? Wha...?!    

08:29.075 --> 08:30.976
All this time,                  
there's somebody in this bar    

08:31.011 --> 08:33.979
who's so mean, so nasty,        
so full of hate                 

08:34.014 --> 08:36.448
that they could take on Hill    
in one second.                  

08:36.482 --> 08:39.183
    Well, I don't know, Sam,    
  I'm kind of busy right now.   

08:40.687 --> 08:43.087
What about Carla?               
She can be pretty mean.         

08:43.123 --> 08:45.557
  Good idea, Woody, good idea.  

08:45.592 --> 08:47.459
    Carla, come here,           
      I got a job for you.      

08:47.494 --> 08:49.194
Yeah, what do you want me to do?

08:49.229 --> 08:50.996
                I want you to   
                get even for me.

08:51.031 --> 08:54.266
     I want you to take all your
meanness, all your nastiness,   

08:54.300 --> 08:55.668
                     and unleash
                it on that...   

08:55.702 --> 09:00.172
            knobby-headed weasel
                John Allen Hill.

09:00.206 --> 09:02.274
You want                        
I should make him cry?          

09:02.308 --> 09:03.242
                        Yeah.   

09:04.277 --> 09:06.979
                 That's perfect.

09:07.013 --> 09:09.348
                  Yeah, make the
                 little man cry.

09:09.382 --> 09:10.382
     Yeah!                      

09:10.417 --> 09:12.584
Consider it done.               

09:12.619 --> 09:14.653
 Yeah, right, now, how are you  
     going to make him cry?     

09:14.688 --> 09:17.556
        You don't think         
    I can make somebody cry?    

09:17.624 --> 09:19.391
     No, actually, I don't.     

09:23.196 --> 09:25.964
Maybe you're right.             

09:28.535 --> 09:30.636
    Uh, say, Rebecca.           

09:30.670 --> 09:32.037
                Mm-hmm?         
When you were                   

09:32.072 --> 09:35.507
a little girl, why <i>did</i> you      
stop riding that pony?          

09:37.510 --> 09:40.913
    Was it because              
    you got too fat?            

09:40.980 --> 09:44.183
Just too damned fat?            

09:44.217 --> 09:48.687
So damned fat you broke         
the back of a horse?            

09:50.890 --> 09:51.857
What's the matter, Becks?       

09:51.891 --> 09:54.360
Your eyes seem a little shiny.  

09:54.394 --> 09:56.462
    (quavering): It's just an   
        allergy or something.   

09:57.997 --> 10:01.166
                      (sobbing):
            If anybody needs me,
        I'll be in my office.   

10:09.376 --> 10:11.777
        You know, I really like 
            Cheetos, but, uh... 

10:11.811 --> 10:13.345
Orange fingers?                 

10:15.782 --> 10:17.549
    I hate that, too.           

10:17.584 --> 10:20.052
At home I use a great big spoon.

10:20.086 --> 10:21.987
         I'll try that.         

10:24.724 --> 10:26.692
          What's this?          

10:26.726 --> 10:28.494
    Oh, that's a flier          
that Mr. Clavin wanted me       

10:28.528 --> 10:30.195
to pass around to the customers.

10:30.230 --> 10:31.730
Well, why didn't you?           

10:31.765 --> 10:33.599
      Because it's a flier      
that Mr. Clavin wanted me       

10:33.633 --> 10:35.501
to pass around to the customers.

10:35.535 --> 10:38.170
    We've had trouble           
      in that area before.      

10:38.204 --> 10:39.338
                "Tune in tonight

10:39.372 --> 10:42.074
        "to catch letter carrier
        Cliff Clavin recreate   

10:42.108 --> 10:43.542
             "the historic first
                mail delivery   

10:43.576 --> 10:44.576
                on the Boston   
                     Post Road."

10:44.611 --> 10:45.611
     (chuckles)                 

10:45.645 --> 10:46.845
    "This is a proud moment     

10:46.880 --> 10:48.981
        for Cliff Clavin        
      and every American."      

10:49.049 --> 10:50.716
            Hey, it's right now.

10:50.750 --> 10:51.917
                  Let's tune in.

10:51.951 --> 10:53.752
 Oh, this is a great            
 <i>Barnaby Jones,</i> though.         

10:53.787 --> 10:55.921
 This is the one where he goes  
    undercover as a swinger     

10:55.955 --> 10:58.023
    to solve a jewel heist.     

10:58.058 --> 10:59.291
                Well, we'll, uh,
            flip back and forth.

10:59.325 --> 11:01.360
     All right.                 

11:01.394 --> 11:03.762
        ANNOUNCER:              
     The crowd here at the      
 Central Post Office is waiting 

11:03.797 --> 11:06.065
    for letter carrier          
        Clifford Clavin,        

11:06.099 --> 11:08.934
    who we understand           
is an award-winning equestrian. 

11:11.071 --> 11:13.038
        Mr. Clavin seems        
    to be running late          

11:13.073 --> 11:15.808
      and his whereabouts       
     are currently unknown.     

11:15.842 --> 11:16.942
        In other news...        

11:16.976 --> 11:19.011
Ooh, I hope everything's okay   
with Cliffie.                   

11:19.045 --> 11:21.313
So, uh, Barnaby's a swinger?    
                Ha, wait till   

11:21.348 --> 11:25.417
you see him. He wears           
hip-huggers, gold               
chains, platform shoes.         

11:25.452 --> 11:29.855
        (phone ringing)         

11:29.889 --> 11:31.890
    Cheers.                     

11:31.925 --> 11:33.792
Oh, yeah, hang on,              
just a second.                  

11:33.827 --> 11:35.427
Hey, Mr. Peterson,              
it's Mr. Clavin.                

11:38.498 --> 11:39.999
    Cliffie, where are you?     

11:40.033 --> 11:42.468
      I don't know, Norm,       
 somewhere in the combat zone.  

11:42.502 --> 11:44.770
Naked! Naked! Naked!            

11:44.804 --> 11:46.605
              Hey, Norm, you got
             to come and get me.

11:46.639 --> 11:48.207
    This horse has got          
    a mind of its own.          

11:48.308 --> 11:49.975
(horn honks, horse neighs)      
             Whoa!              

11:50.010 --> 11:51.844
        (tires screech)         

11:52.912 --> 11:55.814
  Man... Cliffie's in trouble.  

11:55.849 --> 11:57.983
I better go look for him.       

11:58.018 --> 12:01.286
    Shoot, they never           
      rerun this episode.       

12:02.756 --> 12:04.523
    I don't think I've seen     
    the ending of this one.     

12:04.591 --> 12:06.658
         The jewels are         
      in the dog's collar.      

12:06.693 --> 12:08.627
      Oh. Thank you, Phil.      

12:10.630 --> 12:11.930
 Gee, Carla, you were up there  
        with Hill               

12:11.965 --> 12:13.032
  a long time. What happened?   

12:13.066 --> 12:14.867
                 I don't want to
                  talk about it.

12:14.901 --> 12:16.101
            Hey, what did you   
                     say to him?

12:16.136 --> 12:18.170
      Just shut up and get      
out of my way, you stupid,      

12:18.204 --> 12:20.239
     dirt-eating farm boy!      

12:22.342 --> 12:25.177
      Ouch! I'd hate to be      
 on the receiving end of that.  

12:30.917 --> 12:33.318
            (sighs)             

12:33.353 --> 12:34.720
    What is going on?           

12:34.854 --> 12:37.089
In this bar?                    
I don't ask.                    

12:38.591 --> 12:40.526
            (grunts)            

12:42.062 --> 12:43.796
  Now, apparently you're upset  
        over something.         

12:45.899 --> 12:47.499
            (grunts)            

12:47.534 --> 12:50.903
Or not, I don't know            
you that well.                  

12:50.937 --> 12:52.871
  Carla, now just, just relax   
      and try to breathe.       

12:52.906 --> 12:53.939
      Just breathe.             

12:53.973 --> 12:55.941
         (deep breaths)         

12:57.811 --> 13:00.145
All right, now is it            
out of your system?             

13:00.180 --> 13:02.581
All right,                      
now talk to us.                 

13:02.615 --> 13:04.183
        (screams)               
